===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `rm` baraye pak kardan (hazf kardan) file-ha va ya pooshe-ha (ba gozine-haye khass) estefade mishavad.  Ehtiat konid, chon file-haye pak shode ghabel bazgasht nistand! ⚠️

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `rm file.txt` --> 🗑️ Pak kardan yek file be name "file.txt".
    🔹 `rm -r pooshe`  --> 📂 Pak kardan yek pooshe be name "pooshe" va hameye chiz-ha dakhelesh (recursive).
    🔹 `rm -i file.txt` --> 🤔 Ghabl az pak kardan, soal mikonad aya motmaen hastid ya na. (Interactive mode)
    🔹 `rm -f file.txt` --> 💨 File ra be zor pak mikonad, hata agar dastresi nadashte bashid. (Force)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ rm document.pdf

    🔹 Pak kardan file-e "document.pdf".

    $ rm -r pooshe/

    🔹 Pak kardan pooshe-e "pooshe" va hameye file-ha va pooshe-haye dakhele an.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ rm -i important.txt

    🤔 Terminal soal mikonad: "remove important.txt? (y/n)"
    🔹 Agar "y" ra vared konid, file pak mishavad; agar "n" ra vared konid, hich kari anjam nemishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `rm` command is used to remove (delete) files and, with specific options, directories.  Be careful, as deleted files are typically unrecoverable! ⚠️

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `rm file.txt` --> 🗑️ Delete a file named "file.txt".
    🔹 `rm -r directory` --> 📂 Delete a directory named "directory" and all its contents (recursive).
    🔹 `rm -i file.txt` --> 🤔  Prompts for confirmation before deleting each file. (Interactive mode)
    🔹 `rm -f file.txt` --> 💨 Force removal, even if you don't have write permissions. (Force)

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ rm document.pdf

    🔹 Delete the file "document.pdf".

    $ rm -r directory/

    🔹 Delete the directory "directory" and all the files and subdirectories within it.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ rm -i important.txt

    🤔 The terminal prompts: "remove important.txt? (y/n)"
    🔹 If you enter "y", the file is deleted; if you enter "n", nothing happens.